t in 1833  and came to Lexington  Virginia in 1839 to lead the newly established Virginia Military Institute  He died in March 1890  a few months after his retirement as Superintendent  He was known as the builder and  after the Civil War  rebuilder of VMI  His official correspondence spans the period 1839 1889  with few gaps  The Civil War era and earlier letters survived Gen  David Hunter s destruction of many Institute buildings in June 1864  Smith corresponded with the notable military  educational  and political leaders of his time  making the correspondence a rich resource for scholars  Selected topics  full text  are available below  For additional information about this collection  please contact the VMI Archives  Guide to the Records of Francis H  Smith Full text online  selected correspondence Trip to Europe  1858  Report on Scientific Education in Europe Letterbook transcriptions  June 1859  July 1860 The Armory Commission Letters  1859 1860  Arming Virginia for War  Smith and the Secession Crisis  1860 1861 Selected letters  May 1864  The Battle of New Market   Letter  June 17  1864  To William H  Richardson  Adjutant General of Virginia  Reporting Gen  David Hunter s advance on Lexington  Hunter s Raid    aftermath   A Friendship Lost  The 1865 correspondence of West Point classmates George W  Cullum and Francis H  Smith   War sometimes separates those who were once friends Civil War always does Archives   Records   Superintendents   Francis H  Smith Papers Home Archives   Records   Superintendents   Francis H  Smith Papers Home Archives Records Superintendents     Records of the Superintendent Francis H  Smith Correspondence   Francis H  Smith served for fifty years  1839 1889  as VMI s first Superintendent  Smith was born in 1812  graduated from West Point in 1833  and came to Lexington  Virginia in 1839 to lead the newly established Virginia Military Institute  He died in March 1890  a few months after his retirement as Superintendent  He was known as the builder and  after the Civil War  rebuilder of VMI  His official correspondence spans the period 1839 1889  with few gaps  The Civil War era and earlier letters survived Gen  David Hunter s destruction of many Institute buildings in June 1864  Smith corresponded with the notable military  educational  and political leaders of his time  making the correspondence a rich resource for scholars  Selected topics  full text  are available below  For additional information about this collection  please contact the VMI Archives  Guide to the Records of Francis H  Smith Full text online  selected correspondence Trip to Europe  1858  Report on Scientific Education in Europe Letterbook transcriptions  June 1859  July 1860 The Armory Commission Letters  1859 1860  Arming Virginia for War  Smith and the Secession Crisis  1860 1861 Selected letters  May 1864  The Battle of New Market   Letter  June 17  1864  To William H  Richardson  Adjutant General of Virginia  Reporting Gen  David Hunter s advance on Lexington  Hunter s Raid    aftermath   A Friendship Lost  The 1865 correspondence of West Point classmates George W  Cullum and Francis H  Smith   War sometimes separates those who were once friends Civil War always does Records of the Superintendent Francis H  Smith Correspondence    Francis H  Smith served for fifty years  1839 1889  as VMI s first Superintendent  Smith was born in 1812  graduated from West Point in 1833  and came to Lexington  Virginia in 1839 to lead the newly established Virginia Military Institute  He died in March 1890  a few months after his retirement as Superintendent  He was known as the builder and  after the Civil War  rebuilder of VMI  His official correspondence spans the period 1839 1889  with few gaps  The Civil War era and earlier letters survived Gen  David Hunter s destruction of many Institute buildings in June 1864  Smith corresponded with the notable military  educational  and political leaders of his time  making the correspondence a rich resource for scholars  Selected topics  full text  are available below  For additional information about this collection  please contact the VMI Archives Francis H  Smith Gen  David Hunter s destruction  contact the VMI Archives Guide to the Records of Francis H  Smith Guide to the Records of Francis H  Smith Guide to the Records of Francis H  Smith Full text online  selected correspondence Full text online  selected correspondence Trip to Europe  1858  Report on Scientific Education in Europe Letterbook transcriptions  June 1859  July 1860 The Armory Commission Letters  1859 1860  Arming Virginia for War  Smith and the Secession Crisis  1860 1861 Selected letters  May 1864  The Battle of New Market   Letter  June 17  1864  To William H  Richardson  Adjutant General of Virginia  Reporting Gen  David Hunter s advance on Lexington  Hunter s Raid    aftermath   A Friendship Lost  The 1865 correspondence of West Point classmates George W  Cullum and Francis H  Smith   War sometimes separates those who were once friends Civil War always does Trip to Europe  1858  Report on Scientific Education in Europe Trip to Europe  1858 Letterbook transcriptions  June 1859  July 1860 Letterbook transcriptions  June 1859  July 1860 The Armory Commission Letters  1859 1860  Arming Virginia for War The Armory Commission Letters  1859 1860 Smith and the Secession Crisis  1860 1861 Smith and the Secession Crisis  1860 1861 Selected letters  May 1864  The Battle of New Market Selected letters  May 1864 Letter  June 17  1864  To William H  Richardson  Adjutant General of Virginia  Reporting Gen  David Hunter s advance on Lexington  Hunter s Raid    aftermath Letter  June 17  1864  A Friendship Lost  The 1865 correspondence of West Point classmates George W  Cullum and Francis H  Smith   War sometimes separates those who were once friends Civil War always does A Friendship Lost  War sometimes separates those who were once friends Civil War always does     VMI Foundation Keydet Club Alum